Inner functions
Letâ€™s go back to our initial problem.
We have a function f that is defined like so,

# Returns another function which has the ability to print the value for the symbol `text`
f <- function() {

  text <- "Here!"

  function() {
    print(text)
  }
}

Notice that f returns a function as an output.
Iâ€™m going to assign a name to this inner function to make things a bit easier to explain,

# Returns another function which has the ability to print the value for the symbol `text`
f <- function() {

  text <- "Here!"

  inner <- function() {
    print(text)
  }

  return(inner)
}

The important thing to note here, once again, is that the inner function is not executed, but is instead defined when f is called. So think of â€˜call fâ€™ and â€˜define innerâ€™ as being equivalent statements.
When you run f(), hereâ€™s what happens.
First, you create another function (which I have just named print_text),

print_text <- f()

print_text

function() {
    print(text)
  }
<environment: 0x12004e7b8>


However, something else also happens behind the scenes which you donâ€™t see: upon definition, the inner function creates a snapshot of the free variables (i.e.Â text) in its surrounding context,

{
  text: "Here!"
}

In effect, the inner function â€˜enclosesâ€™ its surrounding context.
This is the closure of inner and this is how inner gets a value for text. This value is maintained even after f finishes executing.
